<section id="medicinal" class="section-padding">
  <div class="container">
    <h3>Medicinal and Traditional Uses</h3>
    <div class="content-grid">
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Leaves</h4><p>Used for treating skin conditions, infections, malaria, and as a natural pesticide.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Bark</h4><p>Used to treat fevers, inflammation, and pain.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Seeds</h4><p>Primary source of neem oil, used for skin diseases, hair care, and in agriculture.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Twigs</h4><p>Used as natural toothbrushes (‚Äúdatun‚Äù) in traditional oral hygiene practices.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Flowers</h4><p>Used in aromatherapy and some traditional Indian recipes for their fragrance and medicinal properties.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Neem Oil</h4><p>Possesses antibacterial, antifungal, and insecticidal properties; widely used in skincare and farming.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

