<section id="environment" class="section-padding bg-light">
  <div class="container">
    <h3>Neem Tree: Environmental Impact</h3>
    <div class="content-grid">
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Air Purifier</h4><p>Absorbs pollutants, reduces carbon dioxide levels, and increases oxygen in the atmosphere.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Pesticide Tree</h4><p>Its natural insecticidal properties reduce the need for harmful chemical pesticides.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Soil Health</h4><p>Improves soil fertility and structure; neem cake is used as an organic biofertilizer.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Drought Resistance</h4><p>Thrives in arid and semi-arid climates with minimal water needs.</p></div>
      <div class="feature-item"><h4>Erosion Control</h4><p>Deep root system helps prevent soil erosion, especially in dry regions.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
<section id="facts" class="section-padding">
  <div class="container">
    <h3>Fun Facts and Myths</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Mythological Significance:</strong> In Hindu mythology, the neem tree is considered the dwelling place of the goddess Sitala, protector against smallpox.</li>
      <li><strong>Village Pharmacy:</strong> Every part of the neem tree‚Äîleaves, bark, seeds, and oil‚Äîhas medicinal use, earning it this nickname in rural India.</li>
      <li><strong>Tree of the 21st Century:</strong> Declared so by the United Nations due to its environmental, medicinal, and agricultural value.</li>
      <li><strong>Natural Mosquito Repellent:</strong> Burning neem leaves is a traditional method for repelling mosquitoes in villages.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

